est U.S. power in strategically critical regions throughout the world. They show how rising and revisionist powers are putting pressure on our frontier allies-countries like Poland, Israel, and Taiwan-to gauge our leaders' commitment to upholding the U.S.-led global order. To cope with these dangerous dynamics, nervous U.S. allies are diversifying their national-security "menu cards" by beefing up their militaries or even aligning with their aggressors. Grygiel and Mitchell reveal how numerous would-be great powers use an arsenal of asymmetric techniques to probe and sift American strength across several regions simultaneously, and how rivals and allies alike are learning from America's management of increasingly interlinked global crises to hone effective strategies of their own.The Unquiet Frontier demonstrates why the United States must strengthen the international order that has provided greater benefits to the world than any in history.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aBalance of power. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / International Relations / General.2bisacsh  aAmerican behavior.  aAmerican credibility.  aAmerican frontier.  aAmerican power.  aChina.  aEurasia.  aIran.  aObama administration.  aRussia.  aU.S. allies.  aU.S. defense.  aU.S. economy.  aU.S. foreign policy.  aU.S. leadership.  aU.S. overseas.  aU.S. policy makers.  aU.S. policy.  aU.S. retrenchment.  aU.S. rivals.  aUnited States.  aWashington.  aalliances.  adeprioritization.  adiplomatic postures.  afrontier alliances.  ageopolitical change.  ageopolitical management.  aglobal alliances.  aglobal geopolitics.  aglobal order.  ainternational order.  ainternational system.  amilitary aggression.  amilitary capabilities.  anational strategic outlook.  aoffshore balancing.  apolitical bo